## Pipeline Operator

The `|>` operator chains transformations. Each step receives the output of the previous:

```
GET /api/data
  |> jq: `{ id: (.params.id | tonumber) }`
  |> pg([.id]): `SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1`
  |> jq: `.data.rows[0]`
  |> handlebars: `<h1>{{name}}</h1>`
```

The output of each step is merged into the current state except:
 - if the output is not an object, it replaces the current state.
 - for the last step, which replaces the current state.

## Variables

Variables let you name reusable middleware snippets and reference them later with the same middleware.

```
jq weatherData = `{
  "latitude": 30.27,
  "longitude": -97.74,
  "temperature": 38.0
}`

pg teamsQuery = `SELECT * FROM teams`

GET /weather
  |> jq: weatherData

GET /teams
  |> pg: teamsQuery
```

Syntax:
```
<middleware> <name> = `<code>`
```

## Built-in Middleware

### jq â€” JSON transformation
```
|> jq: `{ result: .data, count: (.items | length) }`
```

#### JQ execution context

Internally, the JQ middleware wraps every user expression in a filter that separates pipeline state from ambient context:

```
.context as $context | .state | <your expression>
```

This means:
- `.` (dot) inside your expression refers to the current pipeline state â€” the mutable "backpack" containing `.body`, `.params`, `.query`, `.tasks`, etc.
- `$context` is a bound JQ variable giving read-only access to flags, conditions, env, and request metadata.
- The pipeline state (`.`) is the full merged object at that point in the route â€” it includes request fields (`.body`, `.params`, `.query`, `.headers`, `.method`, `.path`) plus any fields added by earlier pipeline steps.

#### Capture outer fields before iteration

Because `.` changes meaning inside JQ iteration constructs (`.[]`, `map`, `reduce`, etc.), fields from the top-level state are **not accessible** once you descend into a sub-expression. This is standard JQ scoping, but it causes a specific problem in WebPipe: the test runner may pre-validate routes with empty or null request fields (e.g., `.body` is `null`), causing "cannot use null as iterable" errors that don't appear during normal HTTP requests.

**Always capture request-level fields into JQ variables before iterating:**

```
# BAD â€” .body is inaccessible inside .tasks[], and may be null during test-runner validation
|> jq: `
  .tasks[] |
  if .id == 1 then .title = (.body.title // .title) else . end
`

# GOOD â€” capture .body before entering .tasks[]
|> jq: `
  (.body) as $body |
  (.params.id | tonumber) as $id |
  [.tasks[] |
    if .id == $id then .title = ($body.title // .title) else . end
  ]
`
```

This applies to `.body`, `.params`, `.query`, `.headers`, and any other top-level state fields you need inside array iteration or `reduce`.

### handlebars â€” Template rendering
```
|> handlebars: `<h1>Hello {{name}}</h1>`
|> handlebars: `{{#each items}}<li>{{this.title}}</li>{{/each}}`
```

Handlebars does not support JavaScript-like property access on arrays. There is no `{{items.length}}` â€” compute counts in a prior `jq` or `lua` step and pass them as a named field (e.g., `itemCount`).

HTML attributes containing special characters like double colons (e.g., `hx-on::after-request`) can conflict with WebPipe's backtick-delimited template parsing. Avoid such attributes in Handlebars templates, or use alternative HTMX patterns (e.g., `hx-on` with a single event name).

Partials can be defined as variables and referenced with `{{>partialName}}`:
```
handlebars cardPartial = `
  <div class="card">
    <h3>{{title}}</h3>
    <p>{{description}}</p>
  </div>
`

GET /page
  |> jq: `{ title: "Hello", description: "World" }`
  |> handlebars: `{{>cardPartial}}`
```

### pg â€” PostgreSQL queries
```
|> pg: `SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1`
|> pg([.id]): `SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1`
|> pg([.firstName, .lastName]): `INSERT INTO users (first_name, last_name) VALUES ($1, $2) RETURNING *`
```
Parameters via inline `pg([expr, ...])` or `.sqlParams` array. Returns `{ rows: [...], rowCount: N }`.

Use `!raw` prefix for raw SQL (bypasses parameter escaping â€” use only with safe, computed values):
```
|> pg([(.keys | map(tostring) | join(","))]): `!raw
  SELECT * FROM employees WHERE team_id::text = ANY(string_to_array($1, ','))
`
```

### fetch â€” HTTP requests
```
# Simple GET
|> fetch: `https://api.example.com/data`

# Dynamic URL
|> fetch("https://api.example.com/users/" + (.params.id | tostring))

# POST with options
|> fetch(
    "https://api.example.com/users",
    {
      method: "POST",
      headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
      body: { name: .name, email: .email }
    }
  )
```

### Cookies â€” Setting response cookies
```
|> jq: `{
  message: "Response with cookies",
  setCookies: [
    "sessionId=abc123; HttpOnly; Secure; Max-Age=3600",
    "userId=john; Max-Age=86400",
    "theme=dark; Path=/"
  ]
}`
```
Set `setCookies` to an array of Set-Cookie header strings. The server applies them to the HTTP response automatically.

### Response headers â€” setHeaders, setCookies
These fields in middleware output are actually applied to the HTTP response:

```
|> jq: `{
  setHeaders: {
    "Location": "/users/123",
    "X-Request-ID": (.headers["x-request-id"] // "generated")
  },
  setCookies: [
    "sessionId=abc123; HttpOnly; Secure; Max-Age=3600"
  ],
  data: {
    id: 123,
    created: true
  }
}`
```

- `setHeaders` adds or overrides response headers.
- `setCookies` adds `Set-Cookie` headers.
- Plain `status` and `contentType` fields are not interpreted by the runtime. They stay in the JSON payload unless your own pipeline reads them.

To set an actual HTTP status, use `result` branch codes:
```
POST /users
  |> pg([.body.name]): `INSERT INTO users (name) VALUES ($1) RETURNING id`
  |> result
    ok(201):
      |> jq: `{
        id: .data.rows[0].id,
        created: true,
        setHeaders: {
          "Location": ("/users/" + (.data.rows[0].id | tostring))
        }
      }`
```

To set a non-200 status from your own logic, create an error and branch on it:
```
GET /users/:id
  |> pg([.params.id]): `SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1`
  |> jq: `
    if .data.rowCount == 0 then
      { errors: [{ type: "notFound", message: "User not found" }] }
    else
      .data.rows[0]
    end
  `
  |> result
    ok(200):
      |> jq: `.`
    notFound(404):
      |> jq: `{ error: .errors[0].message }`
```

Actual response content type comes from middleware output metadata, not a `contentType` field in JSON:

- `handlebars` sets `text/html`
- `gg` sets `image/svg+xml` or `image/png`
- Cached responses preserve the cached content type

`setHeaders: { "Content-Type": ... }` can change the header string, but it does not change how WebPipe serializes the body.

### lua â€” Lua 5.4 scripting
```
|> lua: `
  local id = request.params.id
  return { id = id }
`
```
Helpers available in scripts: `request`, `context`, `getEnv(name)`, `requireScript(name)`, `executeSql(query, params)`, `getFlag(name)`, `setFlag(name, bool)`, `getWhen(name)`, `setWhen(name, bool)`.

`context` is immutable ambient data (flags, conditions, env, request metadata). It is not part of the mutable pipeline state. Do not write to `context` expecting persistence or side effects â€” use `request` for the mutable "backpack" that flows through pipeline steps. `context` is read-only; writes to it are silently ignored.

### js â€” JavaScript (Boa engine)
```
|> js: `
  const userId = request.params.id;
  return { userId };
`
```
Same script helpers as lua: `request`, `context`, `getEnv(name)`, `requireScript(name)`, `executeSql(query, params)`, `getFlag(name)`, `setFlag(name, bool)`, `getWhen(name)`, `setWhen(name, bool)`.

The same `context` vs `request` distinction applies: `context` is read-only ambient data, `request` is the mutable pipeline state.

### auth â€” Authentication
```
|> auth: "login"
|> auth: "logout"
|> auth: "register"
|> auth: "required"
|> auth: "optional"
|> auth: "type:admin"
```

### validate â€” Input validation
```
|> validate: `
  email: email
  name: string(3..50)
  password: string(8..100)
`
```

### cache â€” Response caching
```
|> cache: `
  ttl: 300
  enabled: true
  keyTemplate: user-{params.id}
`
```

### log â€” Logging
```
|> log: `level: debug, includeBody: true, includeHeaders: true`
```

### debug â€” Print state (read-only)
```
|> debug: `optional label`
```

### rateLimit â€” Rate limiting
```
|> rateLimit: `
  keyTemplate: ip-{ip}-route-{method}-{path}
  limit: 100
  window: 60s
`
```

### Parallel execution with @async and join
```
|> fetch: `https://api/users` @async(users)
|> fetch: `https://api/posts` @async(posts)
|> join: `users,posts`
```
Results available at `.async.users` and `.async.posts`.

### gg â€” Chart generation (gramgraph)
```
|> gg({ "type": "svg", "width": 800, "height": 400 }): `
  aes(x: time, y: temp)
    | line()
    | point()
`
```
Supports `"type": "svg"` and `"type": "png"`.

## dispatch â€” Tag-based routing
```
|> dispatch
  case @env(production):
    |> jq: `{ mode: "prod" }`
  case @env(development):
    |> jq: `{ mode: "dev" }`
  default:
    |> jq: `{ mode: "unknown" }`
```

Supports boolean expressions in cases:
```
|> dispatch
  case @when(authenticated) and @when(admin):
    |> jq: `{ access: "admin_panel" }`
  case @when(authenticated):
    |> jq: `{ access: "dashboard" }`
  default:
    |> jq: `{ access: "login" }`
```

Guards can also be used as dispatch cases for data-driven branching:
```
|> dispatch
  case @guard(`.tier == "premium"`):
    |> jq: `{ message: "Premium tier", features: ["all"] }`
  case @guard(`.tier == "standard"`):
    |> jq: `{ message: "Standard tier", features: ["basic"] }`
  default:
    |> jq: `{ message: "Free tier", features: [] }`
```

## result â€” Status-based branching
```
|> result
  ok(200):
    |> jq: `{ success: true }`
  validationError(400):
    |> jq: `{ error: "Validation failed" }`
  authError(401):
    |> jq: `{ error: "Unauthorized" }`
  sqlError(500):
    |> jq: `{ error: "Database error" }`
  default(500):
    |> jq: `{ error: "Internal server error" }`
```

`result` routes execution based on the current `.errors` array:
- If `.errors` is missing or empty, `ok(...)` runs.
- Otherwise WebPipe matches `.errors[0].type` against the branch name, such as `validationError`, `authError`, or `sqlError`.
- If no branch matches, `default(...)` runs.
- The status code in parentheses becomes the HTTP status for that branch, and that branch's pipeline output becomes the new response.

## Middleware error types

`result` only branches on structured pipeline errors stored in `.errors`. Only some middlewares write those branchable error objects. Others abort the request with a top-level runtime/config failure instead.

Branchable `.errors` written into pipeline state:

- `auth` -> `authError { message }`
- `validate` -> `validationError { field, context, rule, message }`
- `pg` -> `sqlError { message, sqlstate?, severity?, query }`
- `fetch` -> `networkError { message, url? }`, `timeoutError { message }`, `httpError { status, message, url }`

Built-in middleware error behavior:

- `jq` -> no `.errors`; failures are usually top-level `middleware_execution_error`
- `auth` -> branchable `authError`; database/config failures can also abort with top-level `database_error` or `config_error`
- `validate` -> branchable `validationError`
- `pg` -> branchable `sqlError`; bad inline args can abort with top-level `middleware_execution_error`; missing DB or empty SQL can abort with top-level `database_error`
- `handlebars` -> no `.errors`; failures are usually top-level `middleware_execution_error`
- `fetch` -> branchable `networkError`, `timeoutError`, `httpError`; bad inline args can also abort with top-level `middleware_execution_error`
- `cache` -> no middleware-specific `.errors` during normal execution
- `lua` -> no `.errors`; failures are usually top-level `middleware_execution_error`
- `js` -> no `.errors`; failures are usually top-level `middleware_execution_error`
- `log` -> no middleware-specific `.errors` during normal execution
- `debug` -> no middleware-specific `.errors` during normal execution
- `join` -> no `.errors`; invalid config aborts with top-level `config_error`
- `graphql` -> no WebPipe `.errors`; invalid config or invalid inline variable args abort with top-level `config_error` or `middleware_execution_error`; GraphQL execution failures are returned in GraphQL response format `{ data, errors }`
- `rateLimit` -> no `.errors`; invalid config aborts with top-level `config_error`; exceeded limits abort with top-level `rate_limit_exceeded`
- `gg` -> no `.errors`; failures are usually top-level `middleware_execution_error`

If a middleware aborts with a top-level runtime/config error, `result` will not catch it. Use `result` only for `.errors` values already present in pipeline state.

Custom middleware output can also create your own branchable errors:
```
|> jq: `{
  errors: [{ type: "customError", message: "Something failed" }]
}`
|> result
  customError(400):
    |> jq: `{ error: .errors[0].message }`
```

## Conditional Execution Tags

Tags control when pipeline steps execute:

```
# Environment-specific
|> jq: `.mode = "debug"` @env(development)
|> cache: `ttl: 0` @!env(production)

# Feature flags
|> jq: `.beta = true` @flag(beta)

# Guards â€” JQ expression in backticks
|> pg: `DELETE FROM users WHERE id = $1` @guard(`.user.role == "admin"`)
|> jq: `. + { bonus: true }` @guard(`.user.credits > 50`)

# Runtime conditions (set by Lua with setWhen)
|> jq: `. + { metadata: true }` @when(add_metadata)

# Boolean expressions
|> jq: `. + { both: true }` @when(feature_a) and @when(feature_b)
|> jq: `. + { either: true }` @when(feature_a) or @when(feature_b)
|> jq: `. + { grouped: true }` (@when(a) or @when(b)) and @when(c)

# Multiple tags on a single step
|> fetch("https://api.example.com/admin") @result(adminData) @when(isAdmin)
```

## @result â€” Named results

Name the output of middleware steps for accumulation:

```
|> pg: `SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1` @result(user)
|> pg: `SELECT * FROM departments WHERE id = $1` @result(department)
|> jq: `{
  userName: .data.user.rows[0].name,
  deptName: .data.department.rows[0].name
}`
```

Named variables auto-name their results:
```
pg getUserQuery = `SELECT * FROM users`
|> pg: getUserQuery
# Result available at .data.getUserQuery
```

## Feature Flags

`featureFlags` is a special pipeline that runs before every route. Use it to set request-scoped flags once, then reference them later with `@flag(...)`, `$context.flags` in JQ, or `getFlag(...)` in Lua.

```
featureFlags =
  |> lua: `
    setFlag("experimental", true)
    setFlag("beta", (math.random() > 0.5))
    return {}
  `

GET /dashboard
  |> jq: `{ experimental: ($context.flags.experimental // false), beta: ($context.flags.beta // false) }`
  |> jq: `. + { betaEnabled: true }` @flag(beta)
```

## @when â€” Runtime conditions

Lua middleware can set transient conditions with `setWhen`:
```
|> lua: `
  setWhen("is_admin", true)
  setWhen("is_mobile", false)
  return request
`
|> dispatch
  case @when(is_admin):
    |> jq: `{ access: "admin" }`
  default:
    |> jq: `{ access: "user" }`
```

Read conditions back in Lua: `getWhen("is_admin")`. Access in JQ: `$context.conditions.is_admin`.

## Variables and Named Pipelines

```
jq myQuery = `{ greeting: "hello" }`
pg usersQuery = `SELECT * FROM users`
handlebars welcomeTemplate = `<h1>Welcome {{name}}</h1>`

pipeline withAuth =
  |> auth: "required"
  |> jq: `. + { authenticated: true }`

GET /protected
  |> withAuth
  |> jq: `{ authenticated: .authenticated, user: .user }`
```

Pipelines can receive inline arguments:
```
pipeline getTeam =
  |> pg: `SELECT * FROM teams WHERE id = $1`

GET /team/:id
  |> getTeam({ sqlParams: [.params.id] })
```

When you call a pipeline with inline args, WebPipe computes the child input first. If the current state and the inline args are both objects, they merge for the child call. Otherwise, the inline args replace the child input.

When the helper returns, its output is fed back into the parent using normal state semantics. If the helper returns an object, it merges into the current state. If it returns an array, scalar, or `null`, it replaces the current state.

For testability, keep shared pipelines pure â€” they should read data from their input (what the caller passes), not from `context`. Since `context` is immutable ambient data and not populated with custom state in pipeline tests (`when executing pipeline ... with input`), a pipeline that reads from `context` instead of its input will silently receive `nil`/empty values. Route-level steps should prepare the data and pass it into the pipeline via normal pipeline call semantics.

