```
import "./lib/users.wp" as users

GET /users
  |> pg: users::listUsers
```

## Configuration

```
config pg {
  host: $WP_PG_HOST || "localhost"
  port: $WP_PG_PORT || "5432"
  database: $WP_PG_DATABASE || "mydb"
  user: $WP_PG_USER || "postgres"
  password: $WP_PG_PASSWORD || "password"
  ssl: false
  initialPoolSize: 10
  maxPoolSize: 20
}

config auth {
  sessionTtl: 604800
  cookieName: "wp_session"
  cookieSecure: false
  cookieHttpOnly: true
  cookieSameSite: "Lax"
  cookiePath: "/"
}

config cache { enabled: true, defaultTtl: 60 }
config log { enabled: true, level: "info" }
config graphql { endpoint: "/graphql" }
```

## GraphQL

```
graphqlSchema = `
  type User { id: ID!, name: String!, email: String! }
  type Query { users(limit: Int): [User!]! }
  type Mutation { createUser(name: String!, email: String!): User! }
`

query users =
  |> pg([.args.limit // .limit // 10]): `SELECT * FROM users LIMIT $1`
  |> jq: `.data.rows`

mutation createUser =
  |> pg([.args.name // .name, .args.email // .email]): `INSERT INTO users (name, email) VALUES ($1, $2) RETURNING *`
  |> jq: `.data.rows[0]`

resolver User.posts =
  |> pg([.parent.id]): `SELECT * FROM posts WHERE user_id = $1`
  |> jq: `.data.rows`
```

Resolver input shape:
- Root `query` and `mutation` pipelines receive GraphQL arguments both flattened at the top level, such as `.id` or `.limit`, and grouped under `.args`.
- Nested `resolver Type.field` pipelines also receive `.parent` for the parent object and `.context` for the caller's request/pipeline state.
- Prefer `.args.foo` in new code. The flattened `.foo` form is kept for backward compatibility.
- Example: `resolver User.posts` should usually read the parent object via `.parent.id`.

GraphQL middleware supports inline variables:
```
|> graphql({ userId: .targetId }): `
  query($userId: ID!) {
    user(id: $userId) { name email }
  }
`
```

GraphQL variables can also be stored and referenced:
```
graphql testMutation = `
  mutation($title: String!, $body: String!) {
    createPost(title: $title, body: $body) { id title }
  }
`
|> jq: `.graphqlParams = { title: .body.title, body: .body.body }`
|> graphql: testMutation
```

The GraphQL endpoint can be called directly via HTTP:
```
POST /graphql
  with body: { "query": "query { users { id name } }", "variables": {} }
```

### DataLoader â€” N+1 query prevention

For nested GraphQL resolvers that would otherwise cause N+1 queries, use the `loader` middleware with a batch pipeline. The loader automatically batches all parent keys and calls the pipeline once.

Define a loader pipeline that receives `{ keys: [...], args: {...}, context: {...} }`:
```
pipeline EmployeesByTeamLoader =
  |> pg([(.keys | map(tostring) | join(","))  , (.args.limit // 10)]): `
    SELECT id, name, email, team_id
    FROM (
      SELECT id, name, email, team_id,
        ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY team_id ORDER BY id) as rn
      FROM employees
      WHERE team_id::text = ANY(string_to_array($1, ','))
    ) ranked
    WHERE rn <= $2
  `
  |> jq: `
    reduce .data.rows[] as $row (
      {};
      .[$row.team_id | tostring] += [$row]
    )
  `
```

The loader pipeline must return a JSON object keyed by parent ID (e.g., `{ "1": [...], "2": [...] }`).

Wire it to a nested type resolver using `loader(.parent.id)`:
```
resolver Team.employees =
  |> loader(.parent.id): EmployeesByTeamLoader
```

`loader(...)` arguments work like this:
- The first argument is a JQ expression evaluated against each parent object. Those values are batched into `.keys`.
- The optional second argument is an object expression passed through as `.args`.

The `loader` middleware provides:
- `.keys` â€” batched values from the first loader argument (e.g., `[1, 2, 3]`)
- `.args` â€” the optional object from the second loader argument (e.g., `{ limit: 5 }`)
- `.context` â€” request context (headers, user, etc.)

Example with GraphQL field arguments:
```
resolver Team.employees =
  |> loader(.parent.id, { limit: .args.limit, offset: .args.offset }): EmployeesByTeamLoader
```

If the resolver is called for teams `1`, `2`, and `3` with `limit: 5`, the loader pipeline receives input like:
```
{ "keys": [1, 2, 3], "args": { "limit": 5 }, "context": { ... } }
```

For debugging, you can also execute the loader pipeline directly in a test by passing that same shape via `with input`.

Best practice for JQ-based loaders: capture `.keys` before any `reduce` or `map` that changes JQ's `.` context. Inside a `reduce`, `.` refers to the accumulator, so `.keys` will be `null` unless you save it first.

```
pipeline MyLoader =
  |> jq: `
    .keys as $keys |         # Capture keys before reduce
    reduce .items[] as $item (
      {};
      if ($keys | contains([$item.id])) then .[$item.id] = $item else . end
    )
  `
```

This turns N+1 queries into exactly 2 queries (one for the parent list, one batched for all children).

## Test DSL

Tests live in the same `.wp` file as routes:

Note: `describe` / `it` blocks use a declarative test DSL. They cannot contain pipeline steps such as `|> debug` or `|> middleware: ...`.

### Safe `it` block shape

Use this exact shape when generating tests:

```
it "does something"
  let userId = 123
  let email = "test@example.com"

  when calling POST /users/{{userId}}
  with headers `{ "x-api-key": "secret" }`
  and with body `{ "email": $email }`
  and with cookies `{ "session_id": "abc123" }`
  and mock pg.createUserQuery returning `{ "rows": [{ "id": 123, "email": $email }] }`
  then status is 200
  and output `.rows[0].email` equals "{{email}}"
```

Treat any other ordering as risky. In particular:

- Do not put `with body`, `with headers`, `with cookies`, or `with input` before `when`.
- Do not rely on pre-`when` test-level mocks. Put test-local mocks after the trigger as `and mock ...`.
- If you need shared mocks for many tests, put them at describe scope with `with mock ...`.

```
describe "feature name"
  # Describe-level variables are shared across all tests in this block
  let sharedVar = "shared across tests"
  let defaultRole = "user"
  let activeStatus = true

  with mock pg.usersQuery returning `{ "rows": [] }`

  it "does something"
    let userId = 123
    let email = "test@example.com"

    when calling GET /users/{{userId}}
    with headers `{ "x-api-key": "secret" }`
    and with body `{ "email": $email }`
    and with cookies `{ "session_id": "abc123" }`
    and mock pg.auditQuery returning `{ "rows": [] }`
    then status is 200
    and status in 200..299
    and contentType is "application/json"
    and output equals `{ "success": true }`
    and output contains `{ "success": true }`
    and output matches `^<p>hello.*</p>$`
    and output `.name` equals "Alice"
    and output `.name` equals null
    and output `.message` contains "feature"
    and output `.items | length` equals 5
    and output `.data.teams | type` equals `"array"`
    and header "X-Request-ID" equals "req-123"
    and header "Set-Cookie" contains `session=alice_token`
    and selector `h1` exists
    and selector `#missing` does not exist
    and selector `h1.title` text equals "Welcome Home"
    and selector `.user-profile` text contains "Logged in as"
    and selector `ul.items > li` count equals 3
    and selector `ul.items > li` count is greater than 0
    and selector `a#login` attribute `href` equals "/login"
    and selector `a#login` attribute `href` contains "/login"
    and selector `a#login[href="/login"]` exists
    and selector `ul.items > li:nth-child(2)` text equals "Item 2"
```

### Let variables

Variables support strings, numbers, booleans, null, and backtick JSON:
```
let name = "Alice"
let count = 42
let active = true
let missing = null
let jsonData = `{"key": "value", "count": 10}`
```

Variables are interpolated with `{{varName}}` in paths, assertions, and string values:
```
it "uses variables"
  let userId = 42
  when calling GET /users/{{userId}}
  then output `.id` equals {{userId}}
  and output `.name` equals "User {{userId}}"
```

Test-level `let` overrides describe-level `let`:
```
describe "scoping"
  let role = "user"

  it "uses describe-level default"
    # role is "user" here

  it "overrides at test level"
    let role = "admin"
    # role is "admin" here
```

Keep `let` declarations at the top of the `it` block, before `when`. Do not interleave `let` with `with body`, `with input`, or test-local mocks.

### JQ expressions in test data

Body, headers, cookies, input, and mock returning values all support JQ expressions. Let variables are accessible as `.varName` or `$varName`:

```
it "uses JQ in body"
  let firstName = "John"
  let lastName = "Doe"
  when calling POST /users
  with body `{
    fullName: (.firstName + " " + .lastName),
    tags: [$firstName, "user"],
    level: (if .score > 80 then "gold" else "silver" end)
  }`
  then status is 200

it "uses JQ in mocks"
  let userId = 42
  let userName = "Alice"
  when executing pipeline getUser
  with input `{ params: { id: .userId } }`
  and mock pg returning `{
    rows: [{
      id: .userId,
      name: .userName
    }]
  }`
  then output `.rows[0].id` equals {{userId}}
```

Use `{{varName}}` for paths and string assertions. Use `$varName` or `.varName` inside backticked structured values. Do not use Handlebars interpolation inside backticked JSON/JQ payloads.

### Query strings in route calls

```
when calling GET /search?q=hello&limit=10
when calling GET /users/{{userId}}/posts?page={{page}}
```

### Executing pipelines and variables directly
```
it "tests a pipeline"
  when executing pipeline myPipeline
  with input `{ "params": { "id": "2" } }`
  then output equals `{ "rows": [...] }`

it "tests a variable"
  when executing variable pg myQuery
  with input `{ "sqlParams": [] }`
  then output `.rows | length` equals 3
```

This is also the easiest way to debug helper pipelines and loaders in isolation. If a pipeline returns HTML, selector assertions work here too.

### Mock targets

```
# Describe-level mocks
with mock query users returning `[{ "id": 1, "name": "Alice" }]`
with mock mutation createUser returning `{ "id": 99 }`
with mock pg.usersQuery returning `{ "rows": [] }`
with mock pg returning `{ "rows": [] }`
with mock pipeline myHelper returning `{ "result": true }`

# Test-level mocks (override describe-level)
it "with override"
  when executing pipeline myPipeline
  with input `{ ... }`
  and mock pg returning `{ "rows": [...] }`
  and mock pg.teamsQuery returning `{ "rows": [...] }`
  and mock pipeline processItem returning `{ "mocked": true }`
```

Mocking guidance:

- Use describe-level `with mock ...` for defaults shared across many tests.
- Use test-level `and mock ...` for per-test overrides after `when`.
- Use named mocks like `pg.getTasksQuery` when a route or pipeline makes multiple `pg` calls.
- Use a generic mock like `pg` only when every call can return the same payload.

### Real config vs. mocks

If the file contains a real middleware config such as `config pg = ...`, the test runner may still try to initialize or connect to that dependency even if all calls are mocked. For pure mock-based tests in environments without that dependency:

- remove or comment out the real config in the test file, or
- move the tests into a `.wp` file that does not configure the live dependency

Do not assume that adding `with mock pg ...` is enough to suppress all real initialization.

### Call assertions (spying)
Call assertions accept the same JQ expression syntax as `with body`, `with input`, and mock return values, so they can reference `let` variables as `.varName` or `$varName`.

```
and call query users with `{ "limit": 10 }`
and call mutation createUser with `{ "name": "Alice", "email": "alice@example.com" }`
and call pipeline processItem with `{ "item": "widget", "quantity": 5, "price": 9.99 }`
```

## Common Pitfalls for Agents

- Test boundaries: `it` blocks are for declarative test setup and assertions only. Do not place `|>` pipeline steps inside a test case.
- Runtime debugging: if the request shape or state flow is unclear, add `|> debug` around the suspicious runtime step, inspect the emitted JSON, then remove it once the issue is understood.
- CLI diagnostics are optional: check whether `webpipe-lsp` is installed before suggesting or invoking it. Do not assume every environment has the `webpipe-lsp` command on `PATH`.
- Test ordering: keep `it` blocks in the canonical order `let` -> `when` -> `with` -> `and mock` -> assertions.
- Silent skips: if a test file reports fewer tests than expected, inspect the block immediately before the missing tests for malformed DSL or bad ordering.
- JQ iteration scoping: inside `.tasks[]`, `map(...)`, or `reduce`, the `.` context changes and top-level state fields like `.body`, `.params`, `.query` become inaccessible. Always capture them into JQ variables (e.g., `(.body) as $body`) **before** entering the iteration. The test runner pre-validates routes with null/empty request fields, so `.body.field` inside an iteration can crash with "cannot use null as iterable" even though runtime requests work fine.
- Loader scoping: in JQ loaders, capture `.keys` or other input fields into variables before `reduce` or similar expressions that change what `.` means.
- Pipeline call semantics are shape-dependent: object outputs from `|> helper` merge into the caller's current state, while arrays, scalars, and `null` replace it.
- Named results: for multi-step routes, prefer `@result(name)` and then read from `data.name` in later jq/handlebars steps and test assertions. This is more reliable than depending on the implicit current state after multiple merges.
- Mock data and static snippets: prefer `jq variableName = \`...\`` for reusable JSON snippets, then reference them with `|> jq: variableName`.
- `context` is read-only: do not write to `context` in Lua/JS expecting mutable shared state or cross-request persistence. Use `request` for pipeline state. Writes to `context` are silently ignored.
- Handlebars has no `.length`: arrays do not expose a `length` property in Handlebars. Compute counts in a `jq` or `lua` step and pass them as a named field (e.g., `todoCount`).
- Special characters in HTML attributes: double colons and other special characters in Handlebars template attributes (e.g., `hx-on::after-request`) can cause parse errors. Use alternative patterns.
- Pipeline testability: pipelines tested via `when executing pipeline ... with input` receive only the explicit input. They cannot read custom data from `context`. Keep shared pipelines pure â€” accept data through input, not `context`.
- Non-ASCII in comments: avoid unicode box-drawing or other non-ASCII characters in `.wp` comments (e.g., `# â”€â”€ Section â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€`). They can silently break the parser and cause entire `describe` blocks to be skipped without error. Use plain ASCII only (e.g., `# --- Section ---`).
- `jq` variables are whole-step only: a `jq variableName = \`...\`` variable can only be used as the entire step expression (`|> jq: variableName`), not embedded inside another jq expression (`|> jq: \`{ foo: variableName }\``). To combine seed data with request fields, use a jq step that builds the full object inline.
- HTMX partial responses: for HTMX apps, mutating endpoints (POST/PUT/DELETE) should return HTML fragments (not full pages) for `hx-swap`. Only the initial page load route needs the full `<html>` document.
- Handlebars partials from variables: a `handlebars varName = \`...\`` variable works as a partial (`{{>varName}}`) only when referenced from inside another handlebars variable template. Inline handlebars steps (`|> handlebars: \`{{>varName}}\``) may fail with "Partial not found". To share template fragments, either inline the template in each step or use a single handlebars variable for the full template.

## Running

```bash
webpipe app.wp                         # Serve on 127.0.0.1:7770
PORT=8080 webpipe app.wp               # Custom port
webpipe app.wp --test                  # Run tests
webpipe app.wp --test --verbose        # Verbose tests
webpipe app.wp --inspect               # Debug mode
command -v webpipe-lsp >/dev/null && webpipe-lsp check app.wp
command -v webpipe-lsp >/dev/null && webpipe-lsp check app.wp --json
```

